arch:note.arch:string: The purpose of the daily journal was to record the activities taking place in a trench each day. This included which loci were excavated, how and why loci were excavated and the ongoing impressions of the relationships among loci. It should be noted that journals record the actions, impressions and ideas of trench supervisors during the excavations. They are not, therefore, the final interpretations or syntheses of the emerging data.

arch:internalDocument.arch:string:
Daily Trench Journal

Area F, Trench 7

June 15, 2005

C. Painter

Today was primarily spent excavating various pit loci throughout the trench as well as a burial. Firstly locus 7199, which was opened yesterday, began being excavated in the western half of the trench. This circular pit was found to abut with burial L7200 on its southern end (the burials northern end) and was excavated roughly 20-30 cm with a small pick and hand trowel. Several soil samples were collected (KT4,5) and a notable find from this locus today was a worked bone needle fragment (KT6).

Also excavation of pit 7193 in the eastern half of the trench was begun today with about 30cm being removed with hand pick and trowels. This locus was also opened a few days ago when it was first noticed and is roughly a bathtub-shaped pit with loose, ashy fine soil. What will need to be determined in the next few days is the relationship of 7193 to a new mud brick wall locus 7209 that was opened today. This burnt mud brick wall appears to have two lines/rows of bricks with a grayish white mortar in between, however the exact width of the wall has yet to be determined. What is clear is the brick line along the western side of the wall which is met with a considerably looser, ashy soil, perhaps residual fill from pit 7199. The full extension of wall 7209 both north and south also has yet to be determined as the brick lines are not as clear on these extreme ends of the locus.

Work was also begun in fill L7204, which is a dark grayish brown (10 YR 4/2) medium to fine silt matrix fill with a medium to well sorting pattern, mud brick debris and <1 cm pebble inclusions. This locus was opened south of wall 7201 in the very southwest corner of the trench to better ascertain the corner of 7201. What was discovered was that the brick lines on the western side of the north-south running wall are much more defined though it may be possible that the other east-west running was not scrapped down enough.

Two new loci were also opened in the northwest corner of the trench, L7205 and 7203. 7205 is a dark gray (10 YR 4/1) fine silty matrix fill that was initially designated as a pit, however upon excavation it was found that this matrix texture and color continued below the uppermost layers of 7203, a light brown (7.5 YR 6/3) coarse fill. I suspect that this upper most layer is simply a dried out bottom layer of the subsurface fill locus 7184 that was excavated some time ago and the area has not been looked at since. In this case then, I am calling 7203 and 7205 as equal loci and the entire area containing these loci was excavated with KT numbers applied to L7205.

Work in closing L7191 also continued today where more surfaces and an additional wall were uncovered. Once L7191 is completed removed I will begin to assign loci in this quadrant.

Finally burial 7200 south of pit 7199 was excavated with the assistance of Bradley. Articulation of the skeleton was especially difficult due to the fact that the body was poorly preserved with the bones immediately flaking when touched with either metal dental pick or small brush. Two total bags were assigned to KT1, one holding the teeth and the other holding the rest of the skeleton marked as "miscellaneous bones." The burial was 100% screened through an 1/8 inch sieve and additional bones fragments were collected from there. Only 2-3 pieces of pottery were found inside the burial pit along with a carbon sample. Also one of the three mud bricks which were found to line the pit on the north, east, and south sides was taken for a flotation sample. At this point the rest of the mud bricks and debris were removed and the locus was closed. No additional finds including graves goods were uncovered.
